\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le K\le1/2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Dark regions are mode-locked; the red area corresponds to chaotic orbits.
 The left and right black triangles correspond to fixed points, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n}=c$
\end_inset

 for some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c.$
\end_inset

 These are orbits of period one.
 The central dark triangle corresponds to orbits of period two, where iteration
 bounces the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 between two values.
 The next largest tongues to the left and right of the center correspond
 to period 3.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 for these two are located at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=1/3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2/3$
\end_inset

.
 After that, a tongue of period 4, anchored at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=1/4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3/4$
\end_inset

; then after than, period 5 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=1/5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $4/5$
\end_inset

, and so on.
 The largest tongue in between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=1/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=1/3$
\end_inset

 tongues is the one anchored at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=2/5$
\end_inset

; it is of period 5.
 The subdivision here follows Farey addition on the Stern-Brocot tree: two
 neighboring fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s$
\end_inset

 add together as 
\begin_inset Formula $(p+q)/(r+s)$
\end_inset

.
 The complete binary tree is generated by starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q=0/1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1/1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The image is fractally self-similar, and there is a tongue anchored at every
 rational value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives a hint of the first mathematical curiosity: the rationals are
 a set of measure zero.
 Yet, for 
\begin_inset Formula $K>0$
\end_inset

, the rationals are mapped to a set that obviously has a measure greater
 than zero.
 How does this work? What about the regions 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in between
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 is irrational? These are hard to talk about, since the rationals are dense:
 in between any two irrationals is another rational.
 The irrationals map to the Cantor Set, built by the middle-third costruction.
 Each successive tongue splits an interval into two; the left and right
 halves organize into an infinite binary tree.
 It's worth calling this tree the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cantor tree
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, its always associated with the Cantor set.
 In the study of fractals and chaotic dynamical systems, both the Farey
 addition and the Cantor tree are pervasive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The circle map corresponds to a simple model of weakly coupled rotators,
 mechanical or electrical.
 This is depicted in the diagram below.
 One is to imagine a strong motor, capable of driving with a fixed frequency
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 The motor is directly attached to a disk (labelled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

driven
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the image below), so that it spins with the motor.
 On the circumfrence of this disk is a weak spring, the other end of which
 is attached to the circumfrence of a second disk, which is free to rotate
 in any way.
 The second disk is placed so that it is in the same plane as the first
 disk (so that the spring is only ever stretched, it is never torqued or
 twisted.) The second disk experiences no friction, and is free to spin,
 in any direction, at any speed.
 It is not hard to imagine that, for a stiff spring, that the second disk
 will be forced to spin synchronouly with the first.
 One can also imagine that, for a weak spring, and the second disk having
 some weight (some moment of inertia), the driving motor will bounce around
 the free-spinning disk in some random, chaotic way.
 
\end_layout

