\begin_layout Standard
Iteration of the circle map generally resembles that of the Feigenbaum map,
 including the transition from the period-doubled to the chaotic region.
 As the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $p\to\infty$
\end_inset

 is reached, the visited points spread out into a non-discrete measure.
 The bin-counts provide an approximation to that measure.
 Suppose there are 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 bins, and one has iterated for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 steps.
 At the end of counting, let 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{m}$
\end_inset

 be the count in bin 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Normalizing by the total count, one has a normalized bincount of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{m}=c_{m}/N$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m}\nu_{m}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The bin numbers can be likewise normalized: write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}=\nu_{m}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=m/M$
\end_inset

.
 The continuum limit is then taken as 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to\infty$
\end_inset

 (the width of each bin is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/M$
\end_inset

).
 For finite 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, this just gives a scattering of points on the unit interval.
 The limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 gives the proper invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}\to\mu\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It is a measure in the sense that the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\mu\left(x\right)dx=1$
\end_inset

 can be taken to exist and be properly defined, for the standard topology
 for the reals on the unit interval.
 It is outside of the scope of this text to demonstrate this limit exists
 and is well-defined.
