\begin_layout Subsection
The PerronFrobenius Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A measure is termed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

invariant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, when it corresponds to the FrobeniusPerron eigenvalue of one, for the
 corresponding transfer operator of the iterated function.
 This section takes a short detour into some modest formalities, to review
 what this last sentence means.
 There is a deep and broad literature on this topic; the goal is to present
 enough of an overview, so that other results in this text can be placed
 in perspective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any given iterated function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[0,1\right]\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, define the transfer operator (alternately called the FrobeniusPeron operator)
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}g\right]\left(y\right)=\sum_{x\in f^{-1}\left(y\right)}\frac{1}{\left|f^{\prime}\left(x\right)\right|}g\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

This busy expression can be understood as follows.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

suitable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 space of functions, with the question of suitability discused further,
 below.
 For the present, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 can be taken as just 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

some function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 itself is a vector space (over the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 denotes the derivative; the reciprocal can be recognized as the Jacobian
 of a change-of-variable, as explained below.
 The sum is just a sum over the pre-image of the indicated point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FrobeniusPeron operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator, in that, for any functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}\left(ag+bh\right)=a\mathcal{L}_{f}g+b\mathcal{L}_{f}h$
\end_inset

.
 As a linear operator, it has a spectral decompostion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
xxxx
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
: in general, the spectrum may have both discrete and continuous parts.
 It may be singular, in that there might be functions 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}k=0$
\end_inset

.
 All of conventional operator theory and theorems about spectra apply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of the transfer operator can be formulated more precisely
 and more generally, by replacing the unit interval by a general space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 endowed with a sigma-algebra of Borel sets.
 The transfer operator can then be seen as the push-forward of the time-evolutio
n operator of the dynamical system.
 These details don't seem to be needed for the current text, and so we stick
 to a slightly plainer language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
