\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lesbesgue measureable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of dynamical systems, it is conventional to take 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as the space of integrable functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 endowed with a norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g\right|=\int_{0}^{1}g\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g\right|<\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is conventional to take 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as the space of integrable functions, employing the standard Lesbegue measure
 on the reals.
 Working with this space, it can be seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is measure-preserving: for any 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, the operator can be understood to be a change-of-variable, so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}g\right]\left(y\right)dy=\int_{0}^{1}g\left(x\right)dx
\]

\end_inset

In this space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is a bounded operator that preserves vector space norms.
 Defining the norm as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g\right|=\int g$
\end_inset

, the above states that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathcal{L}_{f}g\right|=\left|g\right|$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Defining the operator norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert A\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 of operator 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as per standard convetion, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert A\right\Vert =\sup\left\{ c:\left|Ag\right|=c\left|g\right|\mbox{ for all \ensuremath{g\in\mathcal{F}}}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathcal{L}_{f}\right\Vert =1$
\end_inset

.
 From spectral theory, this implies that largest eigenvalue in the spectrum
 is the FrobeniusPerron eigenvalue, and it has a value of one.
 This corresponds to a unique eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{f}\mu=\mu
\]

\end_inset

What makes this special here is that this eigenfunction can be identified
 as the invariant measure of the iterated map.
 It is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

invariant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 doesn't change it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, because it predicts the probability of the location of a point, iterated
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Consider starting with the uniform distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

, selecting values 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 from this distribution, and iterating exactly once, to get 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=f\left(x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\in\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 is given exactly by 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}u\right]\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

.
 This continues likewise: iterating 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 times to get 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

, the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 is given exactly by 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}^{n}u\right]\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

.
 In the large-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 limit, one expects that the transients have died away, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 has settled into it's final periodic or chaotic orbit.
 In this large-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 limit, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}^{n}u\approx\mathcal{L}_{f}^{n+1}u\approx\mu$
\end_inset

, so that the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 is given exactly by 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}\mu\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

.
 This provides an intuitive explanation for what 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 does, and why 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 may or may not have additional eigenvalues.
 If the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one (an automorphism), then it cannot have any additional spectral
 components.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
xxxxxxx
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
homeomorphic one-to-one, onto, continuous in both directions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why? Because, in this case, the transfer operator also preserves the 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{1}$
\end_inset

 norm, and so one may consider 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\int g=0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\left|g\right|\ne0$
\end_inset

 and then one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\mathcal{L}_{f}\left|g\right|=\int\left|g\right|$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{N}\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}^{k}g\right]\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 converges to zero: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{N\to\infty}h_{N}\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

 but it converges no faster than 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

.
 There are no eigenvalues with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
xxxxxxxxxxxxxx
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides the principal eigenvalue, there may be more.
 In general, one can conclude that there will be eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}e_{\lambda}=\lambda e_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is vector-length-conserving, one must have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e_{\lambda}\right|=\int_{0}^{1}e_{\lambda}\left(x\right)dx=0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|\ne1$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e_{\lambda}\right|=\left|\mathcal{L}_{f}e_{\lambda}\right|=\left|\lambda\right|\left|e_{\lambda}\right|$
\end_inset

, which can only be satsified if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|=1$
\end_inset

 or if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e_{\lambda}\right|=0$
\end_inset

.
 Such modes 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 are termed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

decaying
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; they vanish exponentially with time, leaving only the invariant measure
 after repeate applications.
 Explicitly, after 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 iterations, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}^{n}e_{\lambda}=\lambda^{n}e_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{n}=\exp n\log\lambda$
\end_inset

 and using 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

, the log is seen to be negative.
 It is a decay constant, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the elapsed time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decaying modes of a measure-preserving dynamical system describe the
 part of the space that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wanders away
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, never to be returned to.
 They correspond to the dissipative part of the system.
 The Hopf decomposition
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Wikipedia, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Hopf decomposition"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hopf_decomposition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 states that every dynamical system can be decomposed into dissipative and
 conservative parts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A concrete example of a decaying mode can be found in the circle map.
 Consider the map with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 allowing only periodic orbits of period 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, convering to an orbit set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ o_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Selecting initial values 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 from a uniform distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and iterating, the iterates converge onto a delta-function measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{p}\sum_{k}\delta\left(x-o_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

, the sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 being over the periodic orbit.
 This is equivalent to saying that the uniform distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 has an eigenfunction decomposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u\left(x\right)=\mu\left(x\right)+\sum_{\lambda}a_{\lambda}e_{\lambda}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

After 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 iterations, the iterates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 with be distributed according to the probability distribution
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{f}^{n}u=\mu+\sum_{\lambda}a_{\lambda}\lambda^{n}e_{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

with the second term rapidly vanishing.
 Consider starting the iteration with some initial 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 where the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 that does not contain any orbit point 
\begin_inset Formula $o_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, the iterated point will be outside of this interval: 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}\left(x_{0}\right)\notin\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 almost certainly.
 For this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wandered away
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}\mu\left(x\right)dx=0$
\end_inset

.
 The interval corresponds to a dissipative part of the system; what is left
 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conservative system
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

