\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measure and the recurrence time can each be derived from the other.
 More precisely, they are reciprocals of one another.
 The relationship is stochastic, rather than dynamic or deterministic.
 It can be derived as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the steps to needed to obtain the recurrence time.
 One selects a starting point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

, with some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\gg1$
\end_inset

 so that one is assured that any transients altering the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 have decayed away.
 How large should this be? There is a formal way to estimate this; a sketch
 follows.
 The transients correspond to eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

 of the FrobeniusPerron operator; that is, the decaying eigenfunctions
 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\lambda}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}e_{\lambda}=\lambda e_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 The largest eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

 is the one that limits convergence the most.
 To see this, expand any given density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the eigenfunctions, by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x\right)=\mu\left(x\right)+\sum_{\lambda}a_{\lambda}e_{\lambda}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for some constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 After 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 iterations of the transfer operator, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}^{n}\rho=\mu+\sum_{\lambda}a_{\lambda}\lambda^{n}e_{\lambda}=\mu+\lambda_{1}^{n}a_{1}e_{1}+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda_{2}^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 where the eigenvalues were ordered such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1>\left|\lambda_{1}\right|>\left|\lambda_{2}\right|>\cdots$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the invariant measure, as before.
 One then looks for a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 sufficiently large that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\gg\left|\lambda_{1}\right|^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The log of the first eigenvalue is just the Lyapunov exponent; this is
 clear by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda_{1}\right|^{n}=\exp n\log\left|\lambda_{1}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Such a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is sufficient to guarantee that the the transients in the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 have died away, to order 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda_{1}^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Keep in mind that, near saddle points, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 might be very close to one, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 might need to be large, there (possibly hundreds or more, in numerical
 practice.) In most other cases, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to be a few dozen is probably sufficient.
 Equivalently, the Lyapunov exponent is very close to zero, near saddle
 points.
 For seat-of-the-pants calculations, all this theoretical concern can be
 skipped; just take 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to be a few hundred for generating pixmaps.
 Computers are fast; this is not an issue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having obtained such a starting point, one then iterates further, looking
 for a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+\tau}\in\left[x_{n}-\epsilon,x_{n}+\epsilon\right]$
\end_inset

 for the chosen 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 Even though iteration is a deterministic process, we can treat it as if
 it were stochastic, and ask the question, when might the above membership
 hold? The answer is given precisely by the measure.
 A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 randomly selected from the unit interval will land within the interval
 centered on point 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 with the probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(x\in\left[y-\epsilon,y+\epsilon\right]\right)=\int_{y-\epsilon}^{y+\epsilon}\mu\left(s\right)ds
\]

\end_inset

Inverting this, one concludes that, on average, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=1/p\left(x\in\left[x_{n}-\epsilon,x_{n}+\epsilon\right]\right)$
\end_inset

 or, explicitly integrating,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\frac{1}{\int_{x_{n}-\epsilon}^{x_{n}+\epsilon}\mu\left(s\right)ds}
