\begin_layout Subsection
The Borel Set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,\mathcal{B}\right)$
\end_inset

 a measurable space.
 This is defined as a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and a sigma-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Henceforth, we'll take the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to be the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, The task is to find a sigma algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

best
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the circle map 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 for fixed values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The goal is to develop a notation to make it easy to talk about the transfer
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}$
\end_inset

, as it needs an appropriate sigma algebra to avoid awkwardness.
 Let's try constructing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 recursively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\left(x\right)=\left(x+\omega-K\sin2\pi x\right)\mod1
\]

\end_inset

This map is piece-wise continuous; it will generally splinter the unit interval
 into 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 subintervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{k},a_{k+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0=a_{0}<a_{1}<\cdots<a_{N}<a_{N+1}=1$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is continuous on each interval.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2\pi<K$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 will have one local maximum, and one local minimum, corresponding to the
 two turning points in the sine wave.
 In this case, we wish to add 2 more points 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

, at which 
\begin_inset Formula $dC\left(x\right)/dx$
\end_inset

 vanishes.
 Placing these into order gives a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $0=c_{0}<c_{1}<\cdots<c_{M}<c_{M+1}=1$
\end_inset

 where most of the 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset

's are 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

's except for the zero or two 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

's thrown in.
 The goal of defining these intervals is to come up with the covering set
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ C^{-1}\left(y\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 for the inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

covering set
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, the informal idea is that, for any given 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 will always have at least one point in each interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{k},a_{k+1}\right)$
\end_inset

, and sometimes two.
 If there are two, then there is a point 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}<b_{j}<a_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 such that there is exactly one point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{k},b_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 and exactly one in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b_{j},a_{k+1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{x\in C^{-1}\left(y\right)}$
\end_inset

 that appears in the transfer operator can be reinterpreted as a sum over
 these intervals.
 Note that these intervals are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost
\begin_inset Quotes erd
