\begin_layout Subsection
Invariant Measure in the Tongue Region
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $K<1/2\pi$
\end_inset

 the circle map is monotonic increasing.
 It's one-to-one and onto, thus an automorphism.
 This makes things quite easy; in particular, an explicit expression for
 the invariant measure is easy to obtain.
 Define the perturbed diagonal as 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x\right)=x-K\sin2\pi x$
\end_inset

; this is again an automorphism, and thus is easily inverted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(y\right)=p^{-1}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard map is just 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(x\right)=\left[p\left(x\right)+\omega\right]\mod1$
\end_inset

; this inverts as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{-1}\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
\alpha\left(y-\omega+1\right) & \mbox{if }y<\omega\\
\alpha\left(y-\omega\right) & \mbox{if }y>\omega
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The transfer operator takes on a simple form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{C}\rho\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\left|C^{\prime}\left(C^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)\right|}\rho\left(C^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\prime}\left(x\right)=p^{\prime}\left(x\right)=1-2\pi K\cos2\pi x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\prime}\left(C^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The task is to find eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}$
\end_inset

; that is, to find functions 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}e_{\lambda}=\lambda e_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 The first eigenvalue, the PerronFrobenius eigenvalue is one, and the associaed
 eigenfunction is the invariant measure.
 It's obtained by treating the above as an ergodic map.
 That is, we assume the ergodic hypothesis holds.
 Then define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=\lim_{N\to\infty}\frac{1}{N}\sum_{k=0}^{N}\mathcal{L}_{C}^{k}u
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the function returning 1, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}^{k}$
\end_inset

 is the transfer operator repeatedly applied 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 times.
 It is not hard to see that this provides the desired invariant measure;
 namely that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}\mu=\mu$
\end_inset

.
 A fast and dirty sketch of the proof is as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}$
\end_inset

 was designed to leave integrals invariant; that is, it is just a change
 of variable:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\left[\mathcal{L}_{C}f\right]\left(y\right)dy=\int_{0}^{1}f\left(x\right)dx
\]

\end_inset

The change of variable sets 
\begin_inset Formula $y=C\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dy=C^{\prime}\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=C^{-1}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 and then, just to make everything painfully and obviously clear:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}f\left(x\right)dx= & \int_{0}^{1}\frac{1}{C^{\prime}\left(x\right)}f\left(x\right)C^{\prime}\left(x\right)dx\\
= & \int_{0}^{1}\frac{1}{C^{\prime}\left(C^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)}f\left(C^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)dy\\
= & \int_{0}^{1}\left[\mathcal{L}_{C}f\right]\left(y\right)dy
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The absolute value for the Jacobian wasn't needed since the maps are all
 positive.
 Next, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}u=1$
\end_inset

 and from this, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\mathcal{L}_{C}^{k}u=1$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{N}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{k=0}^{N}\mathcal{L}_{C}^{k}u
\]

\end_inset

Convergence is obtained by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{N}-\mu_{N-1}=\frac{\mathcal{L}_{C}^{N}u}{N}
\]

\end_inset

Then, provided that one can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathcal{L}_{C}^{N}u\right|<K$
\end_inset

 for constant 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, this sequence converges and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\lim_{N\to\infty}\mu_{N}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 That it converges to the invariant measure can be see by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}$
\end_inset

 just shifts the sum, so that the difference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{N+1}-\mathcal{L}_{C}\mu_{N}=\frac{u}{N}=\frac{1}{N}
\]

\end_inset

goes to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 That the resulting measure is correct is easily confirmed numerically,
 by comparing the result of bin-counting to the above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From what I can tell, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is not only continuous; it is absolutely continuous and smoothly continuous
 and differentiable and even 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

; but I am too lazy to try to prove this.
 It seems like a boring result.
\end_layout

